ASHLAND DRIVER IN THE PROCESS OF HOOKING UP HOSES TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT, MANAGED TO REVERSE THE HOSES TO WHERE HE WAS ACTUALLY PUMPING PRODUCT FROM THE CUSTOMERS TANK INTO OUT TANKER.  THIS PROCESS CAUSED THE TANK COMPARTMENT TO OVERFLOW.  ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER ESTIMATE APPROXIMATELY 10-15 GALLONS SPILLED ON THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RETRAINED ON COMPANY UNLOADING AND LOADING PROCEDURES.  DRIVER HAS BEEN RETRAINED ON RECOGNIZING PUMP CHARACTERISTICS, TO DETERMINE LIQUID FLOW DIRECTION. DRIVER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO "DOUBLE CHECK" HIMSELF PRIOR TO UNLOADING AND LOADING.  AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL, THE DRIVER AND CUSTOMER HAZMAT TEAM CLEANED UP THE SPILL AND PLACED MATERIALS IN A CONTAINER TO BE DISPOSED OF.

column168: OPERATOR WAS LOADING 29.6% AMMONIUM HYDROXIDE INTO A COMMON CARRIER'S TRAILER.  WHILE COMPLETING THE APPROPRIATE PAPERWORK FOR THE LOAD, HE HEARD A CLANKING NOISE AND SOUND OF LIQUID SPRAY.  HE LOOKED AT THE TRAILER AND SAW LIQUID SPILLING FROM BOTH THE TRANSFER HOSE AND THE TRAILER'S FILL VALVE.  OPERATOR CLOSED A LIQUID FEED VALVE TO THE HOSE, AND THEN DONNED A RESPIRATOR AND CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVES ON THE TRAILER.  OPERATOR INITIATED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES AND CALLED 911 AND THE CORPORATE OFFICE.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND IT WAS DECIDED TO FLUSH THE SPILL WITH WATER, DIRECTING IT AWAY FROM THE WELL.  AFTER APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES, THE ODOR WAS VERY SLIGHT.  NEIGHBORING COMPANY EVACUATED BY THE SHERIFF FOR APPROX. AN HOUR.  APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE AT THE PETRO TRUCK STOP ON INTERSTATE 85, EXIT 22, IN SHORTER, ALABAMA THE TRANSPORT SERVICE COMPANY DRIVER WAS PERFORMING A ROUTINE INSPECTION ON THE VEHICLE AND NOTICED THAT FREE PRODUCT WAS ON THE CARGO TANKER.  THE TRANSPORT SERVICE COMPANY DRIVER PLACED DOWN A BUCKET LINED WITH ABSORBENT PADS TO CATCH ANY FREE PRODUCT THAT MAY RELEASE.  APPROXIMATELY THREE OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE BUCKET PLACED DOWN BY THE DRIVER.  THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT.  TRANSPORT SERVICE COMPANY CONTACTED HEPACO, INC. OF BIRMINGHAM, ALABAMA TO PERFORM AN INVESTIGATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION, HEPACO, INC. DETERMINED IT WAS PRESSURE THAT WAS BEING APPLIED BY A NITROGEN JACKET BLANKET THAT WAS COVERING THE PRODUCT WHICH CAUSED THE RELEASE.  HEPACO, INC. REMOVED THE NITROGEN JACKET AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  TRANSPORT SERVICE COMPANY WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE SLIGHTLY IMPACTED ABSORBENT PADS.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

APPROXIMATELY 25, DRUMS CAME OUT, LANDED ON RAILROAD RIGHT OF WAY, WITH SOME LANDING ON THE ADJACENT PROPERTY.  30 OF THE 80 DRUMS WERE SALVAGEABLE AND WERE PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUMS, AND WILL BE RETURNED TO MANUFACTURER.  THE OTHER 50 DRUMS, CONTAMINATED SOILS, DRUM REMNANTS WERE REPACKAGED INTO 89 DRUMS AND WERE CONSIGNED FOR DISPOSAL AT PERMITTED FACILITY.

CSX TRANSPORTATION'S MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT REPORTED THAT GATX 15264, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS (CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE) WAS RELEASING VAPORS AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN SAVANNAH, GA.  THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT REPORTED THEY DETECTED ODOR COMING FROM AROUND THE MANWAY COVER WHEN PERSONNEL WENT ON TOP OF THE CAR TO MAKE REPAIRS.  THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED CHEMTREC OF THE PROBLEM.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, VOPAK TERMINALS.  VOPAK SENT A PERSON TO INSPECT THE CAR BUT THEY TOOK NO ACTION.  VOPAK NOTIFIED DRT, THE OWNER OF THE PRODUCT AND THE LESSEE OF THE TANK CAR.  DRT ARRANGED FOR A GATX RAIL MOBILE REPAIR UNIT TO RESPOND TO MAKE REPAIRS.  THE GATX REPAIR UNIT RESPONDED ON 06-05.  THEY REPORTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS SPLIT AT THE SEAM.  THEY REPLACED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET, SECURED THE CAR AND PRESSURIZED IT TO CHECK FOR LEAKS.  NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: ACFX 73052, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID, NOS (CRUDE SULFATE TURPENTINE) WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RICE YARD IN WAYCROSS, GA.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER, INTERNATIONAL PAPER, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO THE YARD TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING STEADILY FROM THE MANWAY AND THE PRODUCT RELIEF VALVE. THEY OPENED THE MANWAY COVER AND FOUND THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED BEING COMPLETELY FULL WITH LIQUID.  THEY PUMPED 825 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE CAR INTO 15, 55-GALLON DRUMS.  THEY SECURED THE CAR, WIPED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND RELEASED IT.  THE DRUMS WERE STAGED AT THE YARD AWAITING INTERNATIONAL PAPER'S DISPOSITION.

A CAR INSPECTOR AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN TAMPA, FL REPORTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA AS HE WAS INSPECTING CARS ON A RECEIVING TRACK.  THE TRAINMASTER INSPECTED THE CARS ON THE TRACK AND FOUND THAT CITX35257, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED, ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, HAD A VAPOR LEAK AT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE YARD CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, NITRAM, INC.  NITRAM RESPONDED PERSONNEL TO INSPECT THE CAR BUT THEY COULD NOT REPAIR THE LEAK. NITRAM CONTACTED A RAIL CAR REPAIR COMPANY, RESCAR, TO RESPOND.  RESCAR REPLACED TWO "O" RINGS IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DELIVERY TO NITRAM.

column168: AT APPROX 10:00 AM 06-2-03.  I WAS DISCONNECTING VACUUM LINE FROM STANDPIPE AT THE TRUCK BODY PAINT PLANT, WHEN I CLEARED THE LINE THE PAINT WASTE CAME THROUGH THE PUMP UNIT. DAVID G ANDERSON H-T DRIVER. ARRIVED AT 11:30 AM 06/2/03. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: 1.  INTERMODAL CONTAINER WAS LOADED ONTO A ROLL-OFF CHASIS AND THEN LOADED ONTO OUR ROLL-OFF TRAILER.  INTERMODAL WAS UNUSUALLY HIGH AND IT WAS LOADED WITH LIGHT MATERIALS ON BOTTOM AND HEAVY CEMENT & METAL MATERIALS ON TOP, MAKING IT VERY TOP HEAVY AND TALL.  2.  DRIVER WAS MAKING A RIGHT HAND TURN ON THE INTERCHANGE FROM W/B 10 ONTO THE N/B I-5.  THE RECOMMENDED SPEED WAS 45 MPH AND OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING AT 40 MPH.  3. column168: DRIVER WAS EAST BOUND ON INTERSTATE 12 AT SLIDELL, LA., ON A STRAIGHT, LEVEL STRETCH OF HIGHWAY, DRIVING IN THE RIGHT (OUTSIDE) LANE OF TWO EAST BOUND LANES.  INDICATIONS ARE THAT HE ATTEMPTED TO CHANGE LANES TO THE INSIDE LANE AND IN THE PROCESS STRUCK A 1996 TOYOTA 4 RUNNER THAT WAS ALONGSIDE.  THE TOYOTA WENT OFF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY INTO THE GRASS MEDIAN WHERE IT STOPPED UPRIGHT.  THE ENTERPRISE DRIVER, THROUGH CUTTING BACK TO HIS RIGHT, JACKNIFED, WITH THE UNIT MAKING A 180 DEGREE TURN WHERE IT WENT OFF INTO THE DITCH ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE ROADWAY, TURNED OVER ON IT'S LEFT (DRIVER'S) SIDE AND SLID BACKWARDS INTO SOME TREES.  THE DRIVER WAS KILLED IN THE ACCIDENT WHEN HE WAS EJECTED FROM THE TRACTOR WITH THE TRACTOR ENDING UP PARTIALLY ON HIS BODY.  THERE WAS AN ESTIMATED 10-15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED, HOWEVER; THE PRODUCT DID NOT CONTRIBUTE TO THE DRIVER'S DEATH.

THE HOSE THAT FAILED HAD A SOFT SPOT AT THE REAR OF THE FITTING, THIS HOSE HAS BEEN DESTROYED AND DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO LOOK FOR THIS TYPE OF FLAW PRIOR TO ATTEMPTING DELIVERY USING THESE HOSES.

column168: THE SHIPMENT  WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE PACKAGING FAILURE LEADING TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY WAS NOTICED. THE PACKAGE HAD APPARENTLY GOTTEN WET IN TRANSIT.  THERE WAS ENOUGH MOISTURE TO COMPROMISE THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX ALLOWING THE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE TO COME OUT.  THE PACKAGE CONTAINED 34 AEROSOL CANS CONTAINING VARIOUS TYPES OF FLAMMABLE AND NON FLAMMABLE SUBSTANCES.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE  SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE VIA VOICEMAIL TO SPECIAL AGENT DAVE SHAULFER/FAA/MCI ON 6/16/2003.  THIS IS BELIEVED TO BE HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION.8.UN1791, ISOPROPANOL.3.UN1219, AEROSOL FLAMMABLE.2.1, UN1950, AS WELL AS AEROSOL NON-FLAMMABLE.2.2, UN1950.

THE GASKET WAS REPLACED, AND THE UNIT CONTINUED ON TO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

ONE DRUM DAMAGED RROM FORKLIFT BLADE LOST ABOUT ONE GALLON OR ? CALLED CHEMTREC AND CALLED ASHLAND FOR RETURN.

THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMERS FACILITY AND STAGED THE TRAILER IN THE LOADING AREA.  WHEN THE DRIVER REMOVED THE DUST CAP MOLTEN SULFUR HAD LEAKED BY THE VALVE IN THE DISCHARGE LINE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CHECKED THE HAND-WHEEL TO MAKE SURE THAT THE VALVE WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION.  THE DRIVER WORKED THE HAND-WHEEL BACK AND FORTH AND IT WAS FOUND THE SHAFT ON THE CLOSING MECHANISM WAS BENT.  THIS WOULD NOT ALLOW THE VALVE TO CLOSE ALL THE WAY.  THE DRIVER FINALLY GOT THE VALVE CLOSED BY FORCING THE HAND-WHEEL.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA AROUND THE UNLOADING AREA.  CTL SENT A CREW INTO THE PLANT TO CHIP UP THE HARDEN SULFUR.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER INSPECTION PROCEDURES.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER HOOKED UP DISCHARGE HOSE FROM THE TRAILER TO THE CUSTOMER CONNECTION TO UNLOAD.  WHEN HE OPENED THE EXTERNAL VALVE, THE COTTER PIN HOLDING THE NUT ONTO THE END OF THE VALVE STEM BROKE.  THIS ALLOWED THE NUT TO COME OFF AND WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE VALVE, THE STEM CAME ALL THE WAY OUT.  THIS PERMITTED THE PRODUCT TO SPRAY OUT OF THE STEM OPENING.  THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS IMMEDIATELY CLOSED TO STOP THE LEAK AND THE EXTERNAL VALVE WAS CORRECTED AND UNLOADING WAS COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  IT IS UNUSUAL FOR THE COTTER PIN TO SHEAR OFF ON THE EXTERNAL VALVE SHAFTS. PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP BY A CONTRACTOR FOR DISPOSAL.

EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING PRODUCT WHEN HE OVERFILLED THE TANK, CAUSING A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A CONTAINMENT AREA.  CLEAN UP WAS DONE BY OUR EMPLOYEE AND THE EMPLOYEE AT WHITE'S CONSTRUCTION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

ASHLAND DRIVER MADE DELIVERY TO THE CUSTOMER AT TANDEM TECHNOLOGIES.  THE CUSTOMER INDICATED THAT THE STORAGE TANK WOULD HOLD THE INCOMING PRODUCT. DURING THE UNLOADING THE STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED.  50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WHICH WAS CONTAINED IN THEIR DIKE WALL.  CUSTOMER THEN MADE ROOM FOR REMAINING PRODUCT AND DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED.

column168: ASHLAND DRIVER MADE A BULK DELIVERY TO THE CUSTOMER, ALVITY SPECIALTY.  THE CUSTOMER GAUGED THEIR STORAGE TANK AND DETERMINED THE TANK WOULD HOLD INCOMING CONTENTS. column168: DRIVER WAS LOADING MEDICAL WASTE IN HIS TRUCK AT A CUSTOMER FACILITY WHEN HE NOTICED SOME LIQUID ON THE FLOOR.  UPON INVESTIGATING, HE FOUND A LEAKING BOX HE PICKED UP AT A PREVIOUS STOP.  THE DRIVER APPLIED ABSORBENT TO SOAK UP THE LIQUID.  HE REPACKED THE LEAKING BOX.  THE TRUCK WAS DECONTAMINATED AFTER UNLOADING AT THE PLANT.

THE DRIVER STAGED THE LOADED TRAILER IN THE OFF-LOADING AREA AND STARTED TO OFF-LOAD INTO THE CUSTOMERS SULFUR PIT. THE CUSTOMERS SULFUR OFF-LOADING CANNON WAS PLUGGED AND WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE DISCHARGE VALVE ON THE TRAILER AND THE FLOW OF MOLTEN SULFUR STARTED IT FILLED THE OFF-LOADING CANNON AND THEN OVERFLOWED INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA BEFORE THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CLOSE THE DISCHARGE VALVE.  PLANT PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED AND AN OPERATOR WAS CALLED OUT TO UNPLUG THE OFF-LOADING CANNON.  PLANT PERSONNEL TOOK FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR CLEANING UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO A CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED ON AWARENESS AND PROPER INSPECTION OF OFF-LOADING CANNON PRIOR TO OFF-LOADING.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, AN ODOR WAS DISCOVERED COMING FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION BY THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM TWO LEAKING FIVE GALLON METAL PAILS WERE DISCOVERED.  APPROXIMATELY, FOUR GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING, NO BLOCKING OR BRACING WAS PLACED TO SECURE THE PAILS CAUSING THEM TO SHIFT INTO ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, ABSORBENT PADS AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND TWO LEAKING PAILS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THERE WAS EVENTUALLY A REACTION IN THE TRAILER AND A FIRE BROKE OUT IN THE TRAILER. column168: THE LOAD CONSISTED OF 10 TOTES OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID. ACCORDING TO THE HAZMAT TEAM, DURING TRANSIT THE COMBINATION OF LOOSE CAPS, TEMPERATURE AND LATITUDINAL CHANGES CAUSED OFF GASSING OF ACID VAPORS.  THE VAPORS CONDENSED ON THE COLD METAL SURFACES (ROOF AND WALLS) AND THEN RAN AND DRIPPED BACK ONTO THE TOTES AND TRAILER FLOOR.  THE TRUCK WAS STOPPED AT THE TRUCKEE SCALES WHERE MATERIAL WAS NOTED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER. H2O ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED IN TO TEST THE MATERIAL WHICH HAD A PH OF 1-2.  THEY THEN COMPLETED A CLEAN-UP AND DECONTAMINATION.  THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED AND DISPOSED OF AS INDUSTRIAL NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED AND THE LOAD WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN RETURNED TO SCHOOL BUS SALES CO. SO THAT THE DAMAGED PLYWOOD ON THE INTERIOR OF THE TRAILER COULD BE REPLACED.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, JUNE 23, 2003, APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE, CHRIS CRUZ, DISCOVERED A LEAK OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID (CRYOGENIC) IN HIS VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE WAS AN APRIA HEALTHCARE, ISUZU FRR UNIT #21732. THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO BE A COMING FROM THE NON-SPECIFICATION CARGO TANK, HL190, SERIAL #449, MOUNTED IN THE VEHICLE.  CHRIS CRUZ HAD JUST PULLED UP TO 18026 N CAVE CREEK, SCOTTSDALE, AZ TO MAKE A DELIVERY.  HE PARKED THE TRUCK AND UPON OPENING THE SIDE DOOR FOUND THE LEAK.  HE CHECKED THE AREA FOR ANY OPEN FLAMES OR PEDESTRIAN TRAFFIC.  HE THEN OPENED THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRUCK'S BOX SO THAT THE OXYGEN VAPOR WOULD EVAPORATE.  HE CONTACTED HIS OFFICE IN PHOENIX AND REQUESTED A SUPERVISOR COME TO THE SCENE.  DUE TO THE OPERATION OF THE ROAD RELIEF VALVE AND THE LEAK THE PRESSURE IN THE CARGO TANK RAPIDLY DROPPED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  UPON ARRIVAL OF TRANSPORTATION LEAD, JEFF CUTBIRTH, THEY EXAMINED THE CARGO TANK AND VERIFIED THAT THE LEAK HAD STOPPED.  THEY WAITED FOR APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES TO PROVIDE AMPLE TIME FOR THE OXYGEN CONCENTRATION TO DISSIPATE.  THE TRUCK WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE OFFICE WHERE IT WAS SECURED PENDING ARRIVAL OF THE TANK REPAIR TECHNICIAN.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 9 GALLONS OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID HAD BEEN RELEASED.  THERE WAS NO COLLATERAL DAMAGE AND NO INJURIES INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT.  THE TANK WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE HAD FAILED.  ON 3-29-03 THE CARGO TANK HAD BEEN UNDERGONE PERIODIC INSPECTION BY HERNANDEZ WELDING AND CRYOGENICS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: IN THE VICINITY OF THE ACCIDENT, INTERSTATE 70 IS THE TYPICAL INTERSTATE WITH 2 LANES OF TRAVEL IN EITHER DIRECTION AND A WIDE MEDIAN STRIP SEPARATING THE EAST AND WEST BOUND LANES OF TRAVEL.  PRIOR TO THE "CAME TO REST" POINT THERE IS A WIDE SWEEPING CURVE AND AT THAT POINT A HIGHWAY BRIDGE OVER THE RAILROAD TRACKS.  AN 8' PAVED SHOULDER IS PRESENT ON BOTH THE NORTH AND SOUTH SIDE OF WEST BOUND LANES OF TRAVELS.  THE INSURED VEHICLE WAS A 1997 KENWORTH TRACTOR PULLING A LUBBOCK TANKER TRAILER AND A FRUEHAUF PUP TRAILER TRAVELING WEST BOUND ON INTERSTATE 70.  JUST PRIOR TO THE BRIDGE OVER THE RAILROAD TRACKS, THE ROAD ENTERS THE CURVE TO THE RIGHT AND AT THAT POINT, THE PUP TRAILER UPSET ONTO IT'S LEFT SIDE.  THE INSURED VEHICLE WAS IN THE LEFT PASSING LANE WHEN THE PUP TRAILER UPSET.  THE TRAILER STRUCK THE BRIDGE RAILS AND CONCRETE WALLS OF THE BRIDGE CONTAINING THOSE RAILS, DAMAGING THE BRIDGE CONCRETE ALLS AND RAILS.  THE INSURED VEHICLE CONTINUED AROUND THE CURVE DRAGGING THE UPSET PUP TRAILER STRIKING SEVERAL DELINEATOR POSTS AND FINALLY COMING TO REST APPROXIMATELY 3,200 FEET FROM THE ORIGINAL POINT OF UPSET.  THE PUP TRAILER TANK WAS PENETRATED AND THE PRODUCT AND SPILLED ALONG THE TRAVELED AREA AND ONTO THE GROUND AT THE "CAME TO REST" POINT ABOUT 300' EAST OF MILE POST 64 LEAVING A PRODUCT STAIN ON THE GRASS AREA OF THE MEDIAN.  AT SOME POINT OF TRAVEL, THE PRODUCT IGNITED BUT WAS THEN APPARENTLY SELF EXTINGUISHED.

THE DRIVER STARTED THE UNLOADING PROCESS WHEN THE QRB GASKET STARTED TO LEAK.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PUT A BUCKET UNDER THE VALVE ASSEMBLY TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  THE CUSTOMER ASKED THE DRIVER TO CONTINUE TO UNLOAD AND THEY BROUGHT OVER A PLASTIC DRUM TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  THE UNLOADING PROCESS FINISHED AND THE PRODUCT THAT WAS CONTAINED IN THE PLASTIC DRUM WAS PUMP BACK INTO THE CUSTOMERS TANK.  ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS ON THE CONCRETE UNLOADING PAD APPROX. 1-2 GALLONS THE MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE PLASTIC DRUM.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER INSPECTION OF GASKETS AND DISCHARGE VALVES. THE DRIVE WAS ALSO INSTRUCTED IN SPILL PREVENTION.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING AT THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. FACILITY IN HAGERSTOWN, MARYLAND, A CARTON WAS DISCOVERED WET INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPARENTLY HEAVY FREIGHT HAD CRUSHED THE CARTON AND CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE FREIGHT INSIDE THE CARDBOARD CONTAINER.  ONE CARDBOARD CARTON, WHICH CONTAINED TWO (2) 12-FLUID OUNCE PLASTIC JUGS WERE AFFECTED.  ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. HAZMAT TEAM PLACED THE ENTIRE CARTON, ALONG WITH ITS CONTENTS, INTO ONE (1) TEN-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM TO BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO TWO, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, SIX LEAKING FIFTY-SIX POUND POLY BAGS WERE DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY FOUR POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO IMPROPER PACKAGING BY THE SHIPPER.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A DUST PAN AND A BRUSH. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE FREE PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE THREE RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE SIX LEAKING POLY BAGS WERE TAPED, REPACKAGED AND FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  ONE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED VIA INHALATION TO THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO ST. JOSEPH'S HOSPITAL FOR MEDICAL EVALUATION.  THE BLOOD-WORK RESULTS WERE CLEAR AND THE EMPLOYEE WAS RELEASED WITH NO MEDICAL TREATMENT NECESSARY.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: (A) ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING ON HIGHWAY 63, IN HARDY, ARKANSAS THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TRACTOR-TRAILER LEFT THE ROAD AND BOTH TRAILERS WERE OVERTURNED. THE ARKANSAS STATE POLICE RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE. ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. CONTACTED HAZMAT ONE OF OLATHE, KANSAS TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP. HAZMAT ONE DISPATCHED MALLARD ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF SOUTHAVEN, MISSISSIPPI. DAIL'S WRECKER SERVICE OF RAVENDEN, ARKANSAS RESPONDED TO REMOVE THE TWO OVERTURNED TRAILERS FROM THE SITE AND TO ASSIST MALLARD ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WITH THE TRANSFER OF FREIGHT TO UNDAMAGED TRAILERS. THE SALVAGEABLE FREIGHT WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TERMINAL IN JONESBORO, ARKANSAS. UPON INVESTIGATION, CARDBOARD CARTONS CONTAINING THIRTEEN DAMAGED ONE GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE DISCOVERED. AN UNDETERMINED AMOUNT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. MALLARD ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES REMOVED THE DAMAGED FREIGHT FROM THE SCENE. THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AS A RESULT OF THE PACKAGE FALLING TO THE GROUND, AND TWO OF THE INNER GLASS CONTAINERS FAILING. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FORM RESPONSIBLE PARTIES.

column58: Basic Material; Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS OF THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED PACKAGE, THAT WAS NOT DECLARED AS DANGEROUS GOODS, IT WAS SUSPECTED THAT THE SHIPMENT MIGHT BE A DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCT. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED REGARDING THE SPILL AND FAXED A COPY OF THE MSDS, WHICH SHOWED THE PRODUCT TO BE A DANGEROUS GOODS PRODUCT. SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO FITZ BUDDE OF THE JFK/FAA, WHO WAS TO INVESTIGATE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1430 CST/20 JUNE SMOKE WAS SEEN COMING FROM AN LD-11 CONTAINER (ALF61165CO) THAT HAD BEEN STAGED BEHIND CARGO FACILITY IN AN OPEN AREA WAITING A DEPARTING FLIGHT.  UPON OPENING THE CONTAINER, 1 BOX WAS FOUND TO BE SMOLDERING.  FIRE EXTINGUISHERS WERE USED AND THE BOX WAS REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER.  THE BOX CONTINUED TO SMOLDER AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO HOUSTON CITY OPERATIONS PERSONNEL AND FAA HAZMAT SPECIALIST, J R CRAIG WERE ONSITE.  PICTURES WERE TAKEN AND FULL REPORT GIVEN TO INSPECTOR CRAIG.   CARGO CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO A SHADED AREA WHERE IT COULD BE OBSERVED.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS OF THE BURNT BOX WAS COLLECTED AND SITED AS REQUESTED BY INSPECTOR CRAIG.  AT ABOUT 1830 CST, SMOKE WAS ONCE AGAIN SEEN COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE LD-11 CONTAINER.  UPON OPENING CONTAINER, A SECOND BOX WAS FOUND SMOLDERING.  FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AGAIN AND EXTINGUISHED THIS SMOKING BOX.  AT THAT TIME, IT WAS DECIDED TO PLACE THIS CONTAINER INSIDE THE COOLER LOCATED IN THE DOMESTIC CARGO FACILITY.  PRODUCT NEVER DID CATCH FIRE - IT JUST SEEMED TO MELT, SMOLDER AND SMOKE BADLY WHEN EXPOSED TO THE AIR.  THE CONTAINER WAS PLACED IN THE COOLER, ALONG WITH ALL THE DAMAGED, BURNT AND MELTED REMAINS AT ABOUT 2000 CST.  AT ABOUT 2130 CST, A THIRD BOX WAS FOUND TO BE SMOLDERING. THIS BOX WAS REMOVED AND THE SMOLDERING BOX WAS EXTINGUISHED WITH LOCAL FIRE EXTINGUISHERS.  FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOT CALLED AT THIS TIME.  THE CONTINENTAL AIRLINES ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED EAGLE CONSTRUCTION TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP OF THIS INCIDENT AS WE HAVE A CONTRACT WITH EAGLE CONSTRUCTION TO DISPOSE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE.  ACCORDING TO DOCUMENTATION, THERE WERE 36 BOXES OF BLEACHING POWDER THAT WAS PACKAGED IN TWO CLEAR PLASTIC BAGS.  THE SMOLDERING DESTROYED 3 BOXES OF BLEACHING POWDER.  6 BOXES HAD ALREADY BEEN FORWARDED TO DESTINATION ON A PREVIOUS FLIGHT AND ARRIVED IN JFK WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THESE 6 BOXES HAVE BEEN ISOLATED IN THE COOLER IN JFK AND HAVE GIVEN NO INDICATION OF ANY FURTHER REACTION.  THE REMAINING 27 BOXES OF BLEACHING POWDER WERE OPENED AND THE CONTENTS PLACED INTO 55-GALLON DRUMS AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE BY EAGLE CONSTRUCTION.  THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WAS RELEASED BY THE FAA FOR FORWARDING TO DESTINATION.  ON JUNE 25, 2003, A SAMPLE OF THE POWDER WAS FORWARDED TO A LABORATORY FOR ANALYSIS.  THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT IS NOW COMPLETE IN JFK (EXCEPT FOR THE BLEACHING POWDER) AND HAS BEEN PUT ON HOLD BY THE U S CUSTOMS AND BORDER PROTECTION ANTI-TERRORISM TEAM.  THE PACKING LIST SHOW TWO DIFFERENT SIZE BOXES CONTAINING THE BLEACHING POWDER.  ACCORDING TO THE PACKING LIST, EACH BOX CONTAINED 14 UNITS PER CASE.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT AT AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S COOPERATION HAS INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S.  THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

AN ESTIMATED 40 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL SPILLED ONTO THE GRAVEL SURFACE PARKING AREA DURING FUELING ACTIVITIES ON JUNE 11, 2003, WHEN A KITSAP TRANSIT FUEL TRUCK OVERFILLED A TRANSIT COACH AT THE ACCESS BASE FACILITY. ASPECT CONSULTING PERSONNEL VISITED THE SITE ON JUNE 12, 13, AND 19, 2003 TO OBSERVE CLEANUP ACTIVITIES.  THE SPILLED DIESEL CAUSED A SURFACE STAIN AREA APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET LONG.  NO VEGETATED AREAS OR WATER BODIES WERE IMPACTED BY THE SPILL.  THE SPILL WAS REPORTED IMMEDIATELY TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY.  KITSAP TRANSIT PERSONNEL RESPONDED AND EMPLOYED RUBBER TIRED BACKHOE EQUIPMENT TO REMOVE THE UPPER 6 INCHES OF GRAVEL AND SOIL FROM THE SPILL AREA.  ASPECT CONSULTING COLLECTED IMPACTED SOIL SAMPLES FOR DISPOSAL CHARACTERIZATION. LABORATORY RESULTS OF INDICATED THAT DIESEL-RANGE HYDROCARBONS WERE DETECTED. ALL DETECTED DIESEL CONCENTRATIONS WERE BELOW THE MTCA METHOD A SOIL CLEANUP.  APPROXIMATELY 22 TONS OF PETROLEUM-IMPACTED SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE OLYMPIC VIEW SANITARY LANDFILL IN BREMERTON, WASHINGTON. KITSAP TRANSIT PERSONNEL RESTORED THE AREA TO ORIGINAL GRADE BY PLACING 20 TONS OF CRUSHED ROCK IN THE EXCAVATED AREAS.  NO ADDITIONAL ASSESSMENT OR REMEDIAL ACTIONS RELATED TO THE DIESEL SPILL ARE WARRANTED.

column168: A VACUUM TRUCK WAS BROUGHT IN FROM CLEAN HARBORS TO REMOVE SODIUM NITRITE CONTAINING MATERIALS FROM TOTES A PARTIAL TOTE OF PHOSPHORIC ACID SOLUTION WAS INADVERTENTLY ADDED TO THE TANKER. THE REACTION BETWEEN THE ACID AND SODIUM NITRITE SOLUTIONS PRODUCED NITROGEN DIOXIDE GAS. THE CONTENTS OF THE TANKER WERE PUMPED TO A PROCESS TANK AND NEUTRALIZED. THE SOLUTION WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE TANKER WITH THE TWO VENTS FROM THE VACUUM PUMP DISCHARGED INTO FULL TOTES CONTAINER A CAUSTIC/ COOLER MIXTURE TO SCRUB THE NO2 GAS. THE INITIAL SURGE OF DISPLACED VAPORS EXCEEDED THE CAPACITY OF THE TOTES AND NO2 GAS ESCAPED TO THE ATMOSPHERES LABELING OF WASTE CONTAINERS AND SEGREGATION FAR EACH SHIPMENT HAS BEEN IMPLEMENTED.

DURING MOVEMENT AT TERMINAL, THE TWO (2) DRUMS WERE PUNCTURED VIA FORKLIFT RESULTING SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED TO TRAILER AND DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED IN OVERPACK DRUMS.  A SPILL CONTRACTOR (FIRST RESPONSE) WAS DISPATCHED AND PROVIDED CLEAN-UP AND DECONTAMINATION OF THE TRAILER FLOOR WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  NO GROUND (SOIL) SURFACES, STORM DRAINS OR WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED.

column168: OUR OIL DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF DIESEL FUEL TO ONE OF OUR CUSTOMER'S VESSELS, THE FV ELIZA.  UPON REACHING THE PORTSIDE OF THE ELIZA HE DROPPED THE HOSE CAUSING THE NOZZLE TO OPEN AND DIESEL FUEL RELEASED ONTO THE DECK OF THE ELIZA.  OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE NOZZLE OFF AND CLEANED THE VESSEL WITH ABSORBENT PADS.  THE U.S. COAST GUARD REPORTED TO THE SCENE AND INFORMED OUR SUPERVISOR THAT A REPORT WOULD NOT BE NECESSARY DUE TO THE SMALL AMOUNT OF FUEL INVOLVED. (THE REPORTING COAST GUARD OFFICER WAS PO3 CHRIS SHUDA FROM THE POINT JUDITH STATION). SINCE THIS INCIDENT WE HAVE INSTALLED A SAFETY CAP AT THE END OF THE NOZZLE TO PREVENT THIS FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: ON JUNE 28, 2003 OUR FUEL SOUTH TANKER OVERTURNED NEAR THE INTERSECTION OF SLAPPEY BLVD AND OAKRIDGE ROAD, IN ALBANY, DOUGHERTY COUNTY, GEORGIA.  THE TANKER WAS NOT PUNCTURED OR BREACHED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.  HOWEVER APPROXIMATELY 30 TO 50 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED FROM DOME LIDS. THE CITY OF ALBANY EMERGENCY SERVICE RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT, STABILIZED THE TANKER AND SECURED THE AREA.  A LOCAL WRECKER SERVICE DRILLED THE TANKS SO THE REMAINING PRODUCT COULD BE OFF-LOADED INTO ANOTHER TANKER.  AFTER OFF-LOADING THE REMAINING PRODUCT, THE TANKER WAS RIGHTED AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.  ABSORBENT USED TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE PRODUCT WAS PLACED INTO A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER BY THE LOCAL RESPONDERS.  THE ROLL-OFF WAS SAMPLED BY TRG ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTING, LLC OF ALBANY, GEORGIA AND THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE THOMASVILLE LANDFILL FOR DISPOSAL.

PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS GARY GRAGG AND KEVIN GAREN DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A PLASTIC GAMBRO HEALTH CARE LAB BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THIS LAB BOX WAS MARKED "DIAGNOSTIC SPECIMENS PACKED IN COMPLIANCE WITH IATA PACKING INSTRUCTIONS 660 THIS AREA INVOLVED WAS THOROUGHLY CLEANED WITH BLEACH BEFORE NORMAL OPERATION WERE RESUMED. THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND RAGGED THE SHIPMENT INTO TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS THEN FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION CLEAR OF SCENE 0410 THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE THE HAZMAT OFFICE AT WILMINGTON OHIO

ON 06/07/2003 AT 0011 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH AN ODOR OF PERFUME WAS REPORTED AT DOOR "B" 36 OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVER, WILMINGTON, OH 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS GARY GRAGG AND KEVIN GAREN DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE THEY REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN A SMALLER FIBERBOARD BOX THAT CONTAINED 1 X 16 OZ GLASS BOTTLE WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE OF "UNO" PERFUME. THE CLOSURE ON THIS BOTTLE WAS NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THIS BOTTLE STATED "FLAMMABLE". THE CLOSURE ON THIS BOTTLE CAME LOOSE ALLOWING IT TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 3 OZ OF ITS CONTENTS. THE REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. HE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED. CLEAR OF SCENE:0045 THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTN OHIO.

ON 06/05/2003 AT 1148 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH AN ODOR OF PAINT WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING "C" (PRIMARY BRAVO) OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN THOMAS CASPER DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  HE REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION HE FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN 2 X 3.35L METAL PAINT CANS WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES OF "MULAC LACORAMA NEUTRAL BASE".  THE CLOSURES ON THESE CANS WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURES ON THESE CANS CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THEM TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 4.5 L OF THEIR CONTENTS.  WE HAVE RECEIVED A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS FOR THIS SHIPMENT CLASSIFYING THE PRODUCT AS "FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S., 3, UN1993 PG III".  HE REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WERE THREE EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 1300.  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.  A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

GCTX 413142, JUNE 6, 2003, SOUTH EAST DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, FRIDAY JUNE 6, 2003 AT STONEY CREEK YARD IN TRAILER, PA, DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION, FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIALIST, JOSEPH CONNOLLY NOTED SPILLAGE ON SIDE OF TANK CAR GCTX 413142 CONTAINING LOAD, SULFURIC ACID AS IT STOOD IN OUTBOUND TRAIN H72.  FURTHER EXAMINATION BY FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIALIST, JOE CONNOLLY NOTED DEFECTIVE FITTINGS. SHIPPER CONTACTED AND RESPONDED TO TEMPORARILY REPAIR CAR FOR RETURN TO ORIGINATING PLANT FOR OFF-LOADING AND REPAIR.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  PRIOR TO CAR BEING AUTHORIZED FOR MOVEMENT, THE CAR WAS FURTHER INSPECTED BY CONRAIL'S MANAGER RISK MANAGEMENT, AND REPRESENTATIVE FROM REACT (AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR) WHO NOTED FOLLOWING: ONE OF FOUR LIQUID EDUCTION/INDUCTION PIPE FLANGES (GASKETED AREA) OF THE LIQUID EDUCTION/INDUCTION PIPE FLANGE SECUREMENT STUDS BROKEN; PREVIOUS LEAKAGE EVIDENT FROM BETWEEN THE FLANGES (GASKETED AREA) OF THE LIQUID EDUCTION/INDUCTION PIPE (SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE THAT RESPONDED HAD WRAPPED WHAT APPEARED TO BE A WOVEN GASKET AROUND THE PIPE FLANGE AREA AND SECURED IT WITH WIRE); PREVIOUS LEAKAGE NOTED ORIGINATING FROM AROUND THE MANWAY PLATE GASKET AREA.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE ALSO APPLIED SODA ASH TO THE EFFECTED AREAS ON THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS PULLED FROM H72 AND PLACED ON THE SHOP TRACK AWAITING DISPOSITION.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM DANA RAILCARE (RESPONDING ON BEHALF OF THE SHIPPER) CONTACTED CONRAIL'S MANAGER RISK MANAGEMENT ADVISING THAT HE HAD REPLACED THREE OF FOUR SECUREMENT STUDS ON THE LIQUID EDUCTION/INDUCTION PIPE FLANGE, INCLUDING REPLACEMENT OF THE GASKET.  THE BROKEN STUD, HOWEVER, COULD NOT BE REPLACED IN THE FIELD.  THE FRA HAD ALREADY CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, ADVISING A FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY WOULD BE REQUIRED TO MOVE THE CAR BACK TO THE ORIGINATING PLANT.  FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY "FRA - 0306138" WAS ISSUED, AND CAR TO BE RETURNED TO GENERAL CHEMICAL.

THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE LEADING TO THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL OCCURRED.  THE DRUM WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING CAUSING THE LID SEAL TO FAIL ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

UNIT 313-8560 ARRIVED IN EDINBUGH, IN. FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 13:15 PM. DRIVER NOTICED A BAD SMELL WHEN HE GOT OUT OF THE UNIT AND SAW A LIQUID LEAKING FROM FRONT OF A TRAILER.  HE REPORTED THIS IMMEDIATELY TO THE F.O.S. ON DUTY.  THE F.O.S. JOEL BOYD & CSR LORRAINE RICE STARTED MAKING CALLS.  THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE BILL OF LADING WAS CONTACTED WHO THEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND MSDS SHEETS WERE FAXED TO US.  WE CONTACTED THE CCX LINEHAUL DEPT. AND SAFETY SUPERVISOR.   WE THEN CONTACTED A LOCAL VENDOR-MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES 1-812-358-5160 AND THEY ARRIVED AT 1700 HRS TO DETERMINE ACTION NEEDED.  THEY FOUND (1) ONE 55 GALLON DRUM IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER LEAKING.  THE DRUMS APPEAR TO BE OLD USED DRUMS. THE VENDOR PLACED THIS DRUM INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.

PLEASE SEE HMONE INCIDENT REPORT #A030336/CLAIM #I0303864.  13:05 SARA CALLED IN WITH A LEAKING TRAILER AT THE TA TRUCK STOP ON I-15 EXIT 33 LAS VEGAS, NV.  THE TRAILER IS SETTING AT THE FUEL ISLAND.  SHE ASKED IF THEY COULD MOVE IT.  I TOLD HER THAT IF THEY DO THE MATERIAL WAS GOING TO SPRAY OVER THE PARKING LOT AND IT WOULD BE BEST TO STAY STILL THAT WE HAVE SOME TEAMS IN LAS VEGAS.  THE TRAILER HAS ON IT 22 DRUMS OF UN1993, PG III AN 36 DRUMS OF UN3265, PG III.  THE TRAILER IS LEAKING FORM THE MIDDLE.  13:10 H20 IN LAS VEGAS WAS CALLED I SPOKE TO BILL.  HE WILL RESPOND.  I GAVE HIM THE DRIVER'S CELL NUMBER. 13:12 SARA WAS CALLED AND GIVEN THE ETA. 13:25 BILL CALLED BACK AND ASKED FOR THE DRIVER'S CELL NUMBER AGAIN HE HAD WROTE IT DOWN WRONG.  HE WILL HAVE A MAN THERE IN 15 MINUTES AND HIS TEAM THERE SHORTLY AFTERWARDS. 13:30  SARA WAS CALLED AND GIVEN THE INFORMATION. 15:04 BILL WAS CALLED TO SEE IF HIS TEAM HAD ARRIVED.  THEY ARE ON SITE AND UNLOADING THE TRAILER NOW TO SEE WHAT HAS SPILLED.  17:23 BILL WAS CALLED (702) 396-4148.  THE PM IS RODNEY HIS CELL NUMBER IS  (702) 303-0896. 17:25 RODNEY WAS CALLED.  I GOT HIS VOICEMAIL.  I LEFT HIM A MESSAGE TO CONTACT HMONE.  17:53 RODNEY CALLED IN.  THEY ARE LEAVING THE SITE.  THEY FOUND 7 ROWS FROM THE FRONT A NEW 55 GALLON POLY DRUM THAT HAS 2 CLEAN SPLITS IN IT.    IT LOOKS LIKE NOTHING DAMAGED THE DRUM IT JUST WAS A BAD DRUM THAT SPLIT IN 2 PLACES.  AS ESTIMATED 20 GALLONS RELEASED.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN 85-GALLON OVERPACK AND PLACED BACK ON THE TRAILER.  THE TRAILER HAD A PAD LOCK ON IT BUT THE CA REGULATION AND THE UNIT IS HEADING FOR CA.  THEY PLACED THEIR PPE AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL INTO A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM AND THAT IS BEING TAKEN TO H20'S YARD FOR DISPOSAL.  18:04 SARA WAS CALLED AND UPDATED.

column168: A TEMPORARY CARGILL EMPLOYEE PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD THE IBC WITH A FORKLIFT. AS HE BACKED OUT OF THE TRAILER, THE BOTTOM OF THE IBC CAUGHT THE DOCK PLATE AND SLIDE OFF THE FORKS AND TIPPED OVER FORWARD ON ITS SIDE.  THE FORKS HAD NOT BEEN RAISED TO THE APPROPRIATE LEVEL.  THE FILL CAP BUNG POPPED OFF AND APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.  THE CARGILL EMPLOYEE ASKED OUT DRIVER FOR HELP.  OUR DRIVER REPLACED THE BUNG TO STOP THE LEAK.  CARGILL TOOK RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE RESPONSE, CLEAN UP AND COORDINATED THE ACTIVITY WITH LOCAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES.  ON 6/27/03, WE FOLLOWED UP WITH DENNIS ASELEGE OF CARGILL (937-497-4215).  HE ADVISED THAT THE TEMPORARY EMPLOYEE WAS NO LONGER WITH THE COMPANY.  STEPS ARE ALSO BEING TAKEN TO RETEST THE IBC AND WE FOLLOWED UP WITH OUR DEPARTMENT HEADS RESPONSIBLE FOR PACKAGING THIS PRODUCT AS PREVENTIVE ACTION.

CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER NITRAM VIA CHEMTREC.  NITRAM RESPONDED PERSONNEL AND A CONTRACTOR RESCAR TO CHECK THE CAR. WILSON STATED THE CHEMICAL DRIPPED FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE AND THERE WAS SOME MOISTURE ON THE GROUND.  THERE WAS NO WATERWAYS OR INJURIES INVOLVED.  GEOFFREY REEDER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONFERENCED WITH MR. WILLIAMS WHO ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS LOCATED AT THE EAST END OF THE ENGLEWOOD YARD.  MR REEDER RESPONDED AND MET WITH MYO STEVE SPENCER.  SPENCER TOOK REEDER TO THE CAR.  REEDER OBSERVED THE CAR WAS LEAKING AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT ABOUT ONE DROP PER MINUTE.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, REEDER FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS BETWEEN THE VALVE SEAT AND THE TANK.  THE VALVE WAS HELD IN PLACE WITH EIGHT ALLEN HEAD BOLTS.  REEDER TIGHTENED THE BOLTS AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT HAD POOLED ON A TIE.  THIS PRODUCT WAS WIPED AWAY WITH A PAPER TOWEL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT ANY PRODUCT HAD SPILLED BEYOND THE TOP OF THE TIE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT AT 2020HRS.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THE CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED.  CHEMTREC WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.

column168: FILE: 2343 F & D, SHIPPER: NEW LIFE TECHNOLOGY, AWB# MCO 18303914252 LCH. ON 7/27/2003 AT 145 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED AT DOOR "B-31"OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OHIO 45177. PARTTIME SPILL TECHNICIANS THOMAS CASPER AND KEVIN GAREN DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THE BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN 4 X 4 L PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES OF "DEOXIDIZER". THE CLOSURES ON THESE BOTTLES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THE CLOSURE ON ONE OF THE BOTTLES CAME LOOSE ALLOWING IT TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 3 OZ OF ITS CONTENTS. THE MSDS THAT ACCOMPANIED THIS SHIPMENT CLASSIFIED THE PRODUCT AS "CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (PHOSPHORIC ACID MIXTURE), 8 UN 1760 PG II" THE SHIPPER FAXED US A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS THAT CLASSIFIED THE PRODUCT AS "CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (PHOSPHORIC ACID MIXTURE), 8,UN 1760, PG III". THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AND DID NOT HAVE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE  CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLEAR OF SCENE 0202 THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

THERE WERE TWO EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. THEY WERE ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND RETURNED TO THEIR WORK AREAS. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED. column168: AT WILCOHESS #933 LOCATED IN ST MATTHEWS, S.C. A CUSTOMER LEFT THE PUMP HANDLE OFF AND DROVE OFF LEAVING FUEL RUNNING.  THE FUEL RAN MOSTLY ON PARKING LOT (TRUCK STOP) SOME DID GO INTO DRAIN THAT FLOWS INTO CATCH POND WHICH IS DESIGNED TO CATCH ANY FUEL SPILLS.  JOHN MCLAUGHEN OF SOUTH CAROLINA DHEC SAID HE THOUGHT 20 TO 25 GALLONS WENT INTO THE DETENTION POND.  NU-WAY INDUSTRIAL WAS BROUGHT IN TO DO THE CLEAN UP.  CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETE TO THE SATISFACTION OF JOHN MCLAUGHEN.  PERSON CAUSING FUEL SPILL WAS NEVER LOCATED.

column168: ON JUNE 29, 2003 @ 1300 PETE HEINTZ WAS FLAGGED DOWN BY A MOTORIST ON I-81 IN VIRGINIA AND TOLD HIM THAT HIS TANK WAS LEAKING.  PETE GOT OFF THE FREEWAY @ EXIT 35 IN CHILHOWIE, VA AND PARKED ON THE SHOULDER.  HE PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK, WHICH WAS IN THE LOCATION OF THE INTERNAL VALVE AND THEN CALLED BOBBY VAUGN.  STATE TROOPERS HAD ALREADY BEEN NOTIFIED AND WERE ON THE SCENE WITH-IN MINUTES.  THE CHILHOWIE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO RESPONDED QUICKLY.  A CONTAINMENT DITCH WAS DUG IN CASE THE LEAK GOT WORSE BUT IT WAS NEVER UTILIZED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CLOSED BOTH SIDES OF THE RAMP AND EVACUATED A MOTEL, 2 GAS STATIONS AND A RESIDENCE CLOSE BY DUE TO VAPORS, WHICH HAD A POTENTIAL TO IGNITE.  THEY ALSO LAID DOWN SOME FOAM TO SUPPRESS THE VAPORS.  GENE GROSECLOSE IS THE FIRE CHIEF OF THE CHILHOWIE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DAVE HAYNES IS THE ASSISTANT FIRE CHIEF.  BOTH MEN WERE ON SITE.  EASTMAN CHEMICAL COMPANY, CENDIAN AND CHEMTREC WERE ALL NOTIFIED. EASTMAN SENT LEE FREEMAN AND CHUCK LAMBERT AS WELL AS CAPTAIN BRIAN RAMSEY OF THE EASTMAN CHEMICAL CO. FIRE DEPARTMENT TO THE SCENE TO OVERSEE THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT.  BOBBY VAUGHN, SHANE HORTON, NEVADA HILTON, AND CHRIS YARBERRY WERE THE TIDEWATER REPRESENTATIVES.  TIDEWATER DID THE TRANSFER. THE TRANSFER WENT SMOOTHLY AND TOOK APPROXIMATELY 40 MINUTES.  PETE TOOK THE LOADED TRAILER TO EASTMAN AND DROPPED IT THERE.  SHANE AND NEVADA TOO THE EMPTY TRAILER TO M-T CLEAN.  BOBBY AND CHRIS STAYED AND HELPED WITH THE CLEAN UP OF THE FOAM ON THE ROAD.  V-DOT CAME AND SPREAD SOME SAND ON THE EXIT RAMP.  AMERICAN ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ON SITE TO DO THE CLEAN UP.  THE SOUTHBOUND SIDE OF THE EXIT WAS OPENED AROUND 1830 AND THE NORTHBOUND SIDE WAS OPENED AROUND 1900.  06/30/03.  INSPECTED TANK AFTER IT WAS CLEANED. THE LEG AND INTERNAL VALVE WERE REMOVED TO INSPECT THE AREA AROUND THE SUMP.  IT WAS FOUND THAT A SECTION APPROX. 3" IN LENGTH OF A SMALL STEAM LINE HAD BEEN PINCHED BETWEEN THE LEG AND SUMP FLANGES.  IT WAS THEORIZED THAT THIS WAS THE MOST LIKELY CAUSE FOR THE LEAK.  THIS WAS THE FIRST RIP SINCE PROFESSIONAL WELDERS CO. HAD DONE SOME WORK ON THE TRAILER.  IT WAS THEORIZED THAT WHEN THE VALVE WAS REINSTALLED THE LINE HAD BEEN PINCHED. THE TRAILER HAD PASSED A PRESSURE TEST BECAUSE THE GASKET HAD SEALED AGAINST THE LINE AND FLANGE BUT THAT WHEN THE TANK WAS LOADED AND IN TRANSIT THE FLEXING OF THE TANK WORKED THE LINE LOSE AND TORE THE GASKET CREATING THE LEAK.  07/01/03.  MARK TURNER FROM PWC CAME TO THE TIDEWATER TERMINAL TO INSPECT THE TANK.  HE ALSO FELT THAT THE PINCHED STEAM LINE WAS THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK.  HE REQUESTED THAT THE TANK BE BROUGHT BACK TO PWC FOR REPAIRS.
XPB DSR M HOFSTETTER DID NOT PUT IN ANY DUNNAGE TO PROTECT THIS SHIPMENT BEFORE IT WAS LOADED BY XPB DSR P JOHNSON.  ONE CAN ON THE SKID RUBBED ON THE SHID NEXT TO IT AND PUT A HOLE IN IT.

column168: FORKLIFT OPERATOR BOB TERRY HAD LOADED SHIPMENT ONTO TRAILER.  SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF THREE (3) DRUMS BANDED ON 1 PALLET.  UPON EXITING PALLET FORK BLADE CAUGHT BOTTOM LIP OF DRUM CAUSING DAMAGE & SUBSEQUENT LEAKING.  UPON OBSERVING DRUM LEAKING BOB TERRY NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR ON DUTY LARRY STOODT. JIM SWEENEY, HEAD CLERK, REPORTED CONTAINER EMHU 234224 WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOORS AT THE CITY OF INDUSTRY INTERMODAL YARD. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE HAZMAT CONTAINMENT AREA AND SECURED PENDING INSPECTION. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE LADING, WHICH WAS MOSTLY MIXED FREIGHT AND SEVERAL QUANTITIES OF REGULATED MATERIALS. A 55 GALLON OPED HEAD DRUM HAD SHIFTED ON A PALLET, AND THE BOLT RING HAD PUNCTURED THE SIDE OF AN ADJACENT FIVE GALLON PAIL OF 3M SCOTCHGRIP, A CONTACT ADHESIVE PRODUCT, THAT RELEASED APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT, WHICH STAYED MOSTLY INSIDE THE CONTAINER ON THE FLOORING WHERE IT HAD DRIED. IT WAS NOTED THERE WAS NO BLOCKING OR BRACING USED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE LADING, WHICH ALLOWED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS TO SHIFT DURING TRANSIT. APL MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL TO WORK THE LADING THE FOLLOWING MORNING. THE DAMAGED FIVE GALLON PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND SECURED. THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE FREIGHT, ALONG WITH THE SALVAGE DRUM, WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER FOR DELIVER TO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.

column168: DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED CONTAINER APHU 456397 HAD BEEN REPORTED LEAKING BY THE ICTF SECURITY FORCES. INSPECTION NOTED APPROXIMATELY A PINT OF PRODUCT HAD DRIPPED THROUGH THE BOTTOM FLOORING ON TO THE PAVEMENT. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. INSPECTION NOTED THE BLOCKING AND BRACING TO BE ADEQUATE. APL MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL TO REWORK THE LOAD AND LOCATE THE LEAKER. WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS, ONE DRUM FROM THE FLOOR TIER WAS LOCATED THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME. INSPECTION FOUND A RAISED FLOOR SCREW, AND IT APPEARS THE DRUM STRUCK THE SCREW WHILE BEING LOADED. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM FOR SECUREMENT. THE FLOOR WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING, INCLUDING THE SALVAGE DRUM, WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER FOR OVER THE ROAD MOVEMENT TO THE LOCAL CONSIGNEE.

column168: RICK SLOANE, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED A YARD CREW WAS SWITCHING OUT A RAILCAR IN THE NORTH END OF THE YARD WHEN THE TANKCAR ACFX 79511 SPLASHED MOTEN PHENOL ONTO A SWITCHMAN. MR. SLOANE REPORTED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE, THE SWITCH FOREMAN WAS STRIPPED AND HOSED DOWN BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO REMOVE THE RESIDUE. BEN RITTER, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS WAS ALSO ON THE SCENE WITH THE EMPLOYEE. MR. RITTER REPORTED THE EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSPORTED TO SACRED HEART HOSPITAL FOR FURTHER EVALUATION. NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE GROUND, ONLY TO THE SURFACE OF THE TANKCAR ACFX 79511. ALL OF THE CHEMICAL EVAPORATED AND DID NOT SOLIDIFY ON THE TANKCAR. MR. SLOANE ADDITIONALLY REPORTED EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNITS WERE CALLED AND THE RESPONSE TO THE INJURED PARTY WAS FIVE TO SIX MINUTES. THE SWITCH FOREMAN WAS IMMEDIATELY STRIPPED AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT STARTED IMMEDIATE DECON OPERATION, AS WELL AS A SOAP AND WATER WASH, AND THE SWITCHMAN WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL. THE MANWAY COVER GASKET ON THE RAILCAR SEEMED TO BE OUT OF PLACE OR DEFECTIVE. MR. SLOANE STATED HE WAS ADVISED BY THE SHIPPER, NOVEON CHEMICAL OF KALAMA, WA., THE LAST LOADING DOCUMENT INDICATED THE MANWAY GASKET WAS RECENTLY REPLACED. MR. SLOANE ADVISED HE MET WITH BEN RITTER AND A BATTALION CHIEF FROM THE EUGENE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO INSPECT THE CAR. INITIAL INSPECTION INDICATED NO MANWAY GASKET WAS IN PLACE ON THE CAR. AFTER THE ARRIVAL OF VINCE HOFFARTH, UP GENERAL CLAIMS REPRESENTATIVE, THE MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED AND CONFIRMED THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISSING. MR. SLOANE ADVISED TOM JOHNSON, OF NOVEN CHEMICAL AND THEY ADVISED THEY WOULD BE RESPONDING THE NEXT MORNING WITH A REPLACEMENT GASKET. ON JULY 1, MGR. C.T.S., R. SLOANE MET WITH REPRESENTATIVES OF THE CHEMICAL SHIPPER (NOVEON CHEMICAL), FEDERAL RAILWAY ADMINISTRATION - HAZARDOUS MATERIALS INSPECTORS, AND ODOT RAIL SAFETY PERSONNEL TO INSPECT THE RAILCAR AND REPLACE THE GASKET. THE SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES DID NOT HAVE AN APPROPRIATE GASKET SO MR/ SLOANE CONTACTED THE RAIL CAR'S CONSIGNEE, DYNEA RESINS OF SPRINGFIELD TO HAVE AN APPROPRIATE GASKET MADE FOR THE CAR. THE REPLACEMENT GASKET WAS RETRIEVED AT DYNEA AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR DELIVERY.

DRIVER NOTICED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM TRAILER WHILE AT A STOP SIGN.  HE PULLED OFF THE MAIN ROAD ONTO A GRAVEL AREA INSIDE OF AN INDUSTRIAL PARK. WHEN HE OPENED THE BACK ON THE TRAILER, THERE WAS A LARGE CLOUD WITH VERY STRONG ACID FUMES.  HE IMMEDIATELY MOVED AWAY FROM THE TRAILER AND CALLED THE TERMINAL.  THE TERMINAL CALLED CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER, AND HMHTTC (HAZMAT CLEANUP TEAM).  DRUMS WERE ON SHRINK WRAPPED SKID, NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED AGAINST MOVEMENT AND IN TRANSIT SKID TURNED OVER, PUNCTURING TWO DRUMS.  DRIVER, DON HEPNER, TAKEN TO HOSPITAL, TREATED AND RELEASED.  IS OK, NO EFFECTS.
